result.description:
The IADP therefore proposes to focus initially on a more immediate set of metrics, and to measure at discipline, Center of Education, and country levels:

•	The number of academic staff who have participated in identifying and/or sharing educational resources associated with IADP interventions;
•	Whether these academic staff found the output/outcome useful on a qualitative scale; 
•	The number of students to whom the IADP has supplied eBooks;
•	Whether these students found them useful on a qualitative scale;
•	The grade point average of students in the same topic areas who have had access to eBooks compared with those who have not;

In doing so, the IADP recognizes that these metrics are essentially outputs in a results chain, whose primary outcome is likely to remain intuitive, at least during the next phase of the Affordable Access Program.
